  "doc_id": "57064",
  "text": "However, in the real world it is more likely that a dataset shows that a large proportion of the population in question have the trait. Where for example 80% of a population has a particular trait, then an individual from this population is very likely to have the trait. Other available datasets in combination with local knowledge and data analysis techniques such as data mining can further narrow the odds. Rather than having directly identified an individual in a dataset, a number of datasets are used to impute the characteristics about which knowledge is sought for that particular individual. The type of data used for this process could be genomic -Nyholt et al. were able to use a similar process to infer information about Watson's ApoE status. If a dataset provides the information that there is for example an 80% chance that an individual has a particular trait, it can significantly aid the process of inference. Although this might not be attribute disclosure in its pure form, it is useful information for a potential data intruder. Moreover, less than fully accurate predictions about individuals in a given population may nonetheless be used as a basis for making decisions. As with non-genomic data, concerns are raised about the use of this type of data by insurance companies, employers and others for genetic discrimination if individuals in disease study cohorts are identified [CITATION_1] .",
